        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging considerations: 
One of the goals of this proposal is to
probe the shape of the outer regions of the CO envelope. The outer
radius of the CO envelope was estimated to be 13.500AU from the
models in De Beck et al. (2010). These models were based on their
single dish CO(2-1), CO(3-2) and CO(4-3) observations. The CO(3-2)
emission will occur closer to the star. At a distance of 1.57 kpc
(Chen et al. 2007) the CO(3-2) will extend over ~9". To both be
able to map the CO(3-2) emission at a resolution sufficient to
resolve changes at the scale of the water maser region (&lt;0.4") while
recovering the full extent of the emission (~9"), we require the
two ALMA configuration plus the ACA (for a resolution 0.2", maximum
 angular scale ~14"). This is confirmed using the CASA simulator.

NOTE: While specified in the time request, the total power antenna
 is in principle not required. If ALMA so decides, the observations
 can be made without the antenna, decreasing the total time request
 to 2 hr main array and 2.7 hr ACA (for a total of 4.7 hours).

Sensitivity requirements: 
The JCMT observations presented in De
Beck et al. (2010) indicate a median flux of ~43 Jy for
CO(3-2). Assuming the flux is uniformly spread over the expected
extent of the CO(3-2) region (~9") this corresponds to
~22.5 mJy/beam (for a beam of 0.2"). Since we will want to detect
the outer extent of the envelope, we request a SNR of 10, or
2.25 mJy/beam rms in 2 km/s channel separation. 

Correlator setup: 
The aim of the proposal is to
image the CO(3-2) emission around VX Sgr. We thus require
 observations in band 7. The linewidth of ~30 km/s is easily
 sufficient for the correlator  setting with the coarsest spectral
 resolution (1.875~GHz total bandwidth,  dual polarization) with a
 factor of two spectral averaging. In band 7 this setting
achieves approximately 1 km/s velocity resolution. The four
spectral windows were chosen to also maximize the continuum
sensitivity and will additionally cover the 13CO(3-2) line.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
