    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The circumstellar envelope of the red supergiant VX Sgr is host to a strong magnetic field. Observations at scales from ~1 to 1000 AU indicate that the magnetic field has a dipole configuration throughout the circumstellar envelope. This is the first clear indication of a strong, large-scale magnetic field in the envelope of an evolved star.

Magnetic fields potentially play an important role in shaping and driving the mass loss of evolved stars. While strong magnetic fields have been observed around, for example, post-AGB jets, the direct shaping effect of magnetic fields has not yet been observed.

By observing the extended envelope of VX Sgr and comparing potential asymmetries with the observed magnetic field configuration it will be possible to provide strong support for the theory that magnetic fields play an important role in the stellar mass-loss mechanism. The best tracer of the circumstellar envelope at large distances is CO, and ALMA will uniquely be able to map the entire envelope of VX Sgr. We will then determine its geometry compared to the magnetic field previously observed in the inner envelope.</prp:abstract>
